`Dim` class uses a raw C++ array but does not perform any boundary checking. This could become a risk of buffer overrun incident.
Minimal case:

    struct test { Dim dim; unsigned attacked; };
    test t { Dim({0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 9, 100}) };
    cout << t.attacked << endl;
    return 0;

If `&t.attacked == &t.dim + 36` and `operator++` in [this line](https://github.com/clab/dynet/blob/master/dynet/dim.h#L50) is evaluated before `operator=`, this might result:

    100

~~~
feature ss01 {
    featureNames {
        name "®";
    };
   [...]
} ss01;
~~~

yields:

~~~
makeotfexe [FATAL] <PSFont-Regular> invalid token (text was "�") [../family.fea 219]
~~~

@readroberts: Hopefully this is not by-design?

